Ford Gobike Data Exploration¶

By Yasser A.Rahman¶

This Dataset is provided for Ford gobike trip data in 2019 for Sab Fransisco city. it has around 183K entries. It's one of the innovative solutions in very congested cities.

Dataset Structure¶

The Dataset has 183,412 rows (each one is equivalent to a single trip) and 16 features associated with each trip. All featres are quite self explanatory.

the last column "bike_share_for_all_trip", which tracks members who are enrolled in the Bike Share for All program for low-income residents.

Main Features of interest¶

we shall consider here that trip duration as the main variable (dependant variable or target) of this dataset. I have chosen to check the inter relationships among age, gender and user types on the target variable.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I will investigate the distribution of the 4 selected fatures in the dataset eash one separately. The main outcome of this step is to scrutinize the 4 features and check if any wrangling stpes are need or no.

Target Feature Distribution (Trip Duration)¶

what is the shape of trip duration distribution?

In [7]:
# Investigate the distribution of trip duration
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, df['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Duration_sec')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')

plt.show()

Trip duration distribution has shown a long tail behaviuor. This indicates a big amount of outliers present in the dataset.

# Applying zoom in to trip duration till 10,000 seconds
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, df['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])

The distibution still shows long tail behaviuor due to very few outliers but with very high values. I have decided to cut out trips with duration greather than 60,000 seconds (100 minutes) in order to focus on majority of bike riders behaviuor

In [9]:
df_new = df.query('duration_sec < 6000')
binsize = 500
bins = np.arange(0, df_new['duration_sec'].max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_new, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Duration_sec')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
x_90 = df_new.duration_sec.quantile(.9)
plt.axvline(x = x_90, color ='red')
plt.xticks([0, 1000, x_90, 2000, 3000, 4000, 5000], rotation=30)
plt.show()

Insight (1)¶

90% of rides are with duration less than 1158 seconds (19 minutes)

The Histogram of the trip duration is right skewed. we have dropped the records of trip duration higher than 6000 second. The resulted histogram has shown a long tail too. In order to investigate the trip duration further, we need to make a logarithmic transfrmation for the x-axis as will be seen in the next step¶
In [10]:
log_binsize = 0.05
bins_log = 10 ** np.arange(2.4, np.log10(df_new['duration_sec'].max()) + log_binsize, log_binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_new, x = 'duration_sec', bins = bins_log)
plt.title('Distribution of Trip Durations')
plt.xlabel('Duration_sec')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.xscale('log')
plt.xticks([500, 1e3, 2e3, 5e3, 1e4], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k'])
plt.show()

The distribution looks a unimodal one with mode around 600 sec (10 minutes ride) and corresponding frequency of a value around 12K. Then it falls gradually till it reaches 2000 second (33 minutes ride)

Insight (2)¶

The most frequent rides in San Fransisco Bike Share is with duration of 10 minutes.

Age Feature Distribution¶

Does Age has any effect on the trip duration?

In [11]:
# Plotting age distribution derived from member's birth year.
binsize = 1
bins = np.arange(0, df_new['member_birth_year'].astype(float).max()+binsize, binsize)

plt.figure(figsize=[8, 5])
plt.hist(data = df_new.dropna(), x = 'member_birth_year', bins = bins)
plt.axis([2009, 1939, 0, 12000])
plt.xticks([1939, 1949, 1959, 1969, 1979, 1989, 1999, 2009], [(2019-1939), (2019-1949), (2019-1959), (2019-1969), (2019-1979), (2019-1989), (2019-1999), (2019-2009)])
plt.title('Distribution of User Age')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Number of Users')
plt.show()

Insight (3)¶

The Age distribution is a unimodal one with its mode around 30 years old. The majority of the riders are between 20 and 40 years. Moreover, there was a positive correlation between age and trip duration till age = 30 and then afterwards, the relationship has reversed and becomae a negative correlation.

Bivariate Exploration¶

We are going here to consider the variation between the main target variable (Trip Duration) and the 3 chosen faetures: age, user type, and gender.

In [14]:
# Investigating the mutual relationship between age and trip duration
plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.scatter((2019 - df_new['member_birth_year']), df_new['duration_sec'], alpha= 0.3,  marker = '.')
plt.axis([0, 85, 0, 6500])
plt.title('Trip Duration versus Age')
plt.xlabel('Age in years')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration in Sec')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
bins_y = np.arange(0, 6500, 500)
bins_x = np.arange(0, 90, 5)
plt.hist2d((2019 - df_new['member_birth_year']), df_new['duration_sec'],
           bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmin=60, cmap='viridis_r')
plt.xlabel('Age in years')
plt.ylabel('Trip Duration in Sec')
plt.colorbar();
plt.show()

Insight (6)¶

It's quite clear that there is an inversely proportional relationship between age and trip duration as it can be observed from the declining distribution of trip duration over age in years.
it's also very obviuos that the main age interval of riders arwe between 20 and 40 years. the peak of that age interval exists on 25-30 years old.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In this section, we shall investigate two relationships:

  • Between trip duration, age and gender
  • Between trip duration, age and user type
In [17]:
# Investigating the relationship among trip duration, age and gender
gender_mark = [['Male', 'v'],['Female', 's'],['Other', 'o']]

for gender, marker in gender_mark:
    df_gender = df_new[df_new['member_gender'] == gender]
    plt.scatter((2019 - df_gender['member_birth_year']), df_gender['duration_sec'], marker = marker, alpha= 0.25)
plt.legend(['Male','Female','Other'])
plt.axis([10, 80, 0, 6000 ])
plt.title('Trip Duration, Gender, and Age')
plt.xlabel('Age')
plt.ylabel('Duration_sec')
plt.show()

Unfortunately, the plot is not quite clear. So, I am going to apply faceting technique to get clearer results.

Conclusion¶

The Analysis has shown the folowing takeaways:

  • The most frrequent usage of bike sharing is around 10 minutes. So, looks it's inteded for short trip as a repalacement for regular trasnportation like bus or cab. This fact has been emphasized by a fact that more than 90% of rides are with duration less than 20 minutes.
  • The age profile for the majority of users are in range of 20-40 years old. with median value around 30 years old.
  • The ratio of male to female is 3:1. while women - in average - have alonger rides (with median value around 500 second).
  • Subscribers have completed more than eight times the number of rides compared to customers who hold single-use or day-ride passes.
